## No TOD here {#sec-no-tod-planned-here}

While the census shows what happened in the past, zoning and district plans together show what we can expect for the future. Data for the new zoning is now available on Edmonton's open data portal. Data for the nodes and corridors of district planning is not available so I have drawn these borders manually based on the images in the Southeast district plan.


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-11_f255a3a5f3982e1e5a896042204b34e1'}

:::


@Fig-zoning-district-plan shows the zoning (as of January 1, 2024) and proposed nodes and corridors within the Avonmore Stop area. I have also overlaid smaller radii to compare Edmonton's plan with BC's new transit-oriented development legislation that will permit 20 storeys within 200m, 12 storeys within 400m and 8 storeys within the full 800m. It is solidly a low-rise zone area, with only some specific sites zoned for any higher density.

Looking at the nodes and corridors map, we can see that there was no effort to include the LRT station within a node or corridor. Instead, there is a parallel secondary corridor running along 75 St and a bit of Argyll Road to the southeast. That means that only 11% of the station area will be covered by this secondary corridor, which is more of a coincidence than anything.


::: {#fig-zoning-district-plan .cell .column-page layout-ncol="2" hash='index_cache/html/fig-zoning-district-plan_9334e1ead80c6c4dad25b82fb9ce1f29'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Zoning as of January 1, 2024](index_files/figure-html/fig-zoning-district-plan-1.png){#fig-zoning-district-plan-1 width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Proposed nodes and corridors from district planning](index_files/figure-html/fig-zoning-district-plan-2.png){#fig-zoning-district-plan-2 width=672}
:::

Land use in the Avonmore Stop area
:::

::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-13_d20ef74b8ff2313c5de346944d28dd85'}

:::


Now, using the zoning data, we can remove plots zoned for parks, fire halls and other jurisdictions, where housing is unlikely to be built, even through a rezoning. @Fig-nodes-corridors-residential shows the coverage of nodes and corridors when we exclude these zones. While there was already low node and corridor coverage, using this map, only 4% of the station area is covered by the secondary corridors that will support up to 8 storeys.


::: {.cell .preview-image hash='index_cache/html/fig-nodes-corridors-residential_bbffdd792ea289c38a94ff5c37c4d3cd'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Nodes and corridors around Avonmore Stop, only residential zones](index_files/figure-html/fig-nodes-corridors-residential-1.png){#fig-nodes-corridors-residential width=672}
:::
:::


## Conclusion

I think it's a significant missed opportunity that there are no policies to encourage higher-density development around rapid transit stations like Avonmore. Even worse than McKernan/Belgravia station, Avonmore stop is not even in a secondary corridor, making it likely that we will not see any additional density beyond the 8 units per lot allowed in the base RS zone.

The district plans are still being edited and will come back to Council in Q2 2024. If you agree that we need more transit-oriented development policies in the district plans, please [email your councillor](https://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/mayor-city-councillors) and sign up for the [Grow Together Edmonton](https://www.gtyeg.ca/) mailing list to stay up-to-date on Edmonton housing news.
